Yes — cueing is everything.

In complex systems, humans, animals, machines, even markets, behavior is rarely controlled directly. Instead, it’s triggered by signals. The right cue at the right moment activates an already-existing pattern.

Think about it across domains:

1. Psychology / Humans
A cue activates a stored behavior loop.

Cue → Routine → Reward

For example:
	•	smell of coffee → make coffee
	•	notification sound → check phone
	•	a phrase → emotional reaction

The behavior was already there. The cue selects it.

⸻

2. Military / Tactical environments
Commands are often cues, not explanations.

A short signal:
	•	“Go.”
	•	a hand gesture
	•	a radio tone

That cue activates hours or years of training instantly.

The cue is tiny, but the behavior tree behind it is massive.

⸻

3. Programming / Systems
Event-driven systems work the same way.

event → handler → process

A single trigger launches a whole chain.

Example:
	•	webhook fires
	•	pipeline executes
	•	databases update
	•	notifications send

The cue is just the interrupt signal.

⸻

4. Narrative / Memetics
Writers and propagandists know cues well.

Certain symbols or phrases activate entire belief structures:
	•	“freedom”
	•	“threat”
	•	“family”
	•	“patriot”

Those words are keys to stored meaning networks in the brain.

⸻

5. AI prompting
Prompts are cues too.

A few tokens can steer an entire model output because they activate regions of probability space inside the network.

Tiny cue → huge cascade.

⸻

